Commentary: has he fallen to the sweep again? Fullish delivery, and he looks to sweep. Loud appeal, and given, but Campbell has reviewed. The line was outside off, turning back in, and he took on the sweep despite this being a fairly full ball. It has definitely passed close to bat, but if there's no inside edge on this, he could be in trouble. UltraEdge seems to indicate a very fine tickle, actually. It might just be the general disturbance with the noise from the sweep. That's what the umpire thinks, and it's three reds on ball tracking. Bangladesh have that breakthrough
Commentary_short: Taijul Islam to Campbell, OUT

Commentary: umpire raises his finger! We're going upstairs because it could be an lbw or a caught dismissal. Full outside off, and he tries to paddle a fine sweep. Takes his front leg across, but he misses the shot. The ball turns sharply, misses the front leg, and hits the back leg before going in the air. The fielder at first slip anticipates the shot and runs behind the keeper to his left, and takes the catch after it pops up from the back leg. The fielders appeal in unison for caught and given. Liton reviews the decision but the TV umpire says that the ball has hit his bat before hitting his leg. Clean catch by first slip, so Liton has to go. Anticipation at its best
Commentary_short: Cornwall to Liton Das, OUT

Commentary: taken? West Indies think it's out. Sarkar has not moved. Umpire does not raise his finger. West Indies review This was an overpitched ball outside off. Sarkar tries to cut. Takes an edge, hits the keeper's gloves, ball pops up in the air, and first slip - Cornwall - dives forward to hold on! This time Illingworth gets it wrong. For what it's worth, Sarkar started to walk as soon as WI reviewed. He knew he had nicked, but it's also his right to stay put if the on-field umpire hasn't given him out. Fair play from all parties. Also the introduction of the part-timer, the captain himself, works
